# Heaps and PriorityQueue in Java

A heap is a **complete binary tree** stored compactly in an array where every parent is 'better' than its children. 'Better' means smaller in a min-heap and larger in a max-heap. The practical payoff: you can always read the best element in O(1) and remove it in O(log n) — which is exactly what a priority queue needs.

## Shape + order — the two heap invariants
```java
// SHAPE: complete binary tree — every level filled left-to-right
// So it is stored perfectly in an array with no wasted slots:
//
//         1          index 0
//       /   \
//      3     2        index 1, 2
//     / \   / \
//    7   4  5   6     index 3, 4, 5, 6
//
// Parent of i  →  (i - 1) / 2
// Left child   →  2*i + 1
// Right child  →  2*i + 2
//
// MIN-HEAP ORDER: heap[parent] <= heap[child]  (root = global minimum)
// MAX-HEAP ORDER: heap[parent] >= heap[child]  (root = global maximum)
```

## Java PriorityQueue — min-heap by default
```java
// Min-heap (natural order)
PriorityQueue<Integer> minH = new PriorityQueue<>();
minH.offer(5); minH.offer(1); minH.offer(3);
minH.peek();    // 1  — O(1), does NOT remove
minH.poll();    // 1  — O(log n), removes minimum

// Max-heap (reverse order)
PriorityQueue<Integer> maxH = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());

// Custom objects — sort by frequency descending
PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> b[1] - a[1]);
```

## Heapify — build a heap from an array in O(n)
```java
// Naive: insert n elements one by one → O(n log n)
// Smart: sift-down starting from the LAST non-leaf upward → O(n)
//
// Why O(n)? Most nodes are near the bottom with short sift-down paths.
// The math: sum of all sift-down work = O(n)  (not O(n log n)).
//
void buildHeap(int[] a) {
    int n = a.length;
    for (int i = n / 2 - 1; i >= 0; i--)  // last non-leaf = n/2-1
        siftDown(a, n, i);
}
```

## Top-K pattern — keep a heap of size k
```java
// Top-K LARGEST elements — use a MIN-heap of size k.
// Mental model: the min-heap is a 'bouncer' that keeps only the
// k biggest seen so far. Anything smaller than the heap's min gets rejected.
//
int[] topKLargest(int[] nums, int k) {
    PriorityQueue<Integer> minH = new PriorityQueue<>();
    for (int n : nums) {
        minH.offer(n);
        if (minH.size() > k) minH.poll();  // evict the current minimum
    }
    // minH now contains exactly the k largest elements
    return minH.stream().mapToInt(Integer::intValue).toArray();
}
// Time: O(n log k)   Space: O(k)
```

## Median of a data stream — two heaps
```java
// Trick: keep a MAX-heap for the lower half and a MIN-heap for the upper half.
// Balance them so sizes differ by at most 1.
//
//  lower (max-heap): [1, 2, 3]    upper (min-heap): [4, 5, 6]
//                          ↑ max of lower ≤ min of upper ↑
//
// Median = average of both tops (even count) or top of larger heap (odd count).
PriorityQueue<Integer> lower = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());
PriorityQueue<Integer> upper = new PriorityQueue<>();

void addNum(int num) {
    lower.offer(num);
    upper.offer(lower.poll());     // balance: push lower's max to upper
    if (upper.size() > lower.size()) lower.offer(upper.poll()); // keep lower >= upper
}
double findMedian() {
    return lower.size() > upper.size()
        ? lower.peek()
        : (lower.peek() + upper.peek()) / 2.0;
}
```

## K-way merge — merge k sorted lists in O(n log k)
```java
// Put the FIRST element of each list into a min-heap.
// Every poll() gives the global minimum; then push the next element
// from the same list. Repeat until heap is empty.
//
List<Integer> mergeKSorted(int[][] lists) {
    // heap stores: [value, listIndex, elementIndex]
    PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.comparingInt(a -> a[0]));
    for (int i = 0; i < lists.length; i++)
        if (lists[i].length > 0) pq.offer(new int[]{lists[i][0], i, 0});
    List<Integer> res = new ArrayList<>();
    while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
        int[] cur = pq.poll();
        res.add(cur[0]);
        int next = cur[2] + 1;
        if (next < lists[cur[1]].length)
            pq.offer(new int[]{lists[cur[1]][next], cur[1], next});
    }
    return res;
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Confusing peek() (O(1), no removal) with poll() (O(log n), removes root)
- Using a max-heap for top-K largest — counterintuitive but correct: min-heap lets you evict the smallest quickly
- Forgetting that Java PriorityQueue is a MIN-heap by default
- Assuming heapify (buildHeap) is O(n log n) — it is actually O(n) because lower nodes do less work
- Index arithmetic: parent = (i-1)/2, left child = 2i+1, right child = 2i+2 — off-by-one off-by-one off-by-one

## Connections
- **Binary Trees**: a heap is a complete binary tree stored in an array
- **Sorting**: heap sort uses heapify + n extractions — O(n log n) in-place
- **Graphs**: Dijkstra's algorithm replaces a visited array with a min-heap on distances
- **Sliding Window**: some window problems use a heap when you need fast max/min updates

